### Wikipedia portal for content related to Illinois

# The Illinois Portal

The [flag of Illinois](/Flag_and_seal_of_Illinois), for your viewing pleasure.

[Illinois](/Illinois) ([/ˌɪlɪˈnɔɪ/](/Help:IPA/English) [ⓘ](/File:En-us-Illinois.ogg) IL-ih-NOY). It's a [state](/U.S._state), if you insist on labels, wedged into the [Midwestern](/Midwestern_United_States) region of the [United States](/United_States). It has the dubious honor of bordering [Lake Michigan](/Lake_Michigan) to its northeast, the relentless [Mississippi River](/Mississippi_River) to its west, and the less famous but equally wet [Wabash](/Wabash_River) and [Ohio rivers](/Ohio_River) to its south. Among the fifty states vying for attention, Illinois boasts the [fifth-largest gross domestic product](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_GDP) (GDP), the [sixth-largest population](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_population), and is the [25th-most expansive in land area](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_area), making it impressively average in size. Its capital is [Springfield](/Springfield,_Illinois), a city centrally located for maximum inconvenience, while its largest urban sprawl, [Chicago](/Chicago), looms in the northeast.

Long before it was a state, this land was home to various [Indigenous cultures](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas) for millennia. The French were the first Europeans to wander in, establishing settlements near the Mississippi and [Illinois](/Illinois_River) rivers during the 17th century. This area, known as the [Illinois Country](/Illinois_Country), was just one piece of their vast colonial puzzle, [New France](/New_France). A century later, the revolutionary war’s [Illinois campaign](/Illinois_campaign) served as a bloody prelude to American dominance in the region. After the [U.S. achieved independence in 1783](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1783)), a treaty that conveniently made the Mississippi River the new national boundary, American settlers began to trickle in from [Kentucky](/Kentucky) by way of the Ohio River. Illinois was subsequently absorbed into the nation's first organized territory, the [Northwest Territory](/Northwest_Territory), and by 1818, it had graduated to [statehood](/List_of_U.S._states_by_date_of_admission_to_the_Union).

The construction of the [Erie Canal](/Erie_Canal) unleashed a wave of commercial activity across the Great Lakes. Then, Illinoisan [John Deere](/John_Deere_(inventor)) invented the self-scouring [steel plow](/Plough), an innovation that brutally tamed the state's rich [prairie](/Prairie), transforming it into some of the most productive—and therefore valuable—farmland on the planet. This agricultural gold rush attracted [immigrant](/Immigration_to_the_United_States) farmers from [Germany](/German_American), [Sweden](/Swedish_American), and other places they were keen to leave. By the mid-19th century, the [Illinois and Michigan Canal](/Illinois_and_Michigan_Canal) and an ever-expanding web of railroads cemented the state's role as a national transportation hub. This was especially true for [Chicago](/Chicago), which, by the late 1800s, was metastasizing at a rate that made it the world's fastest-growing city. By 1900, the siren call of industrial jobs in the northern cities and [coal](/Coal) mining in the central and southern regions drew waves of immigrants from [Eastern](/Eastern_Europe) and [Southern Europe](/Southern_Europe). Illinois became an industrial titan and, to this day, remains a significant manufacturing center. The [Great Migration](/Great_Migration_(African_American)) from the South brought a large Black community, especially to [Chicago](/Chicago), which evolved into a cultural and economic powerhouse. Its sprawling [metropolitan area](/Metropolitan_area), known informally and with grim acceptance as [Chicagoland](/Chicago_metropolitan_area), now contains roughly 65% of the state's 12.8 million residents.

Illinois is home to two [World Heritage Sites](/World_Heritage_Site): the ancient, haunting [Cahokia Mounds](/Cahokia_Mounds) and a piece of the [Frank Lloyd Wright architectural collection](/The_20th-Century_Architecture_of_Frank_Lloyd_Wright). A commendable number of [protected areas](/List_of_protected_areas_of_Illinois) exist, all attempting to preserve what's left of the state's natural and cultural resources. It also houses major centers of learning like the [University of Chicago](/University_of_Chicago), the [University of Illinois](/University_of_Illinois), and [Northwestern University](/Northwestern_University), where people go to become smarter and, ideally, less annoying.

Three [U.S. presidents](/President_of_the_United_States) were residents of Illinois when elected: [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln), [Ulysses S. Grant](/Ulysses_S._Grant), and [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama). In a slightly different category, [Ronald Reagan](/Ronald_Reagan) was born and raised here before finding his political fortunes in [California](/California). The state clings to Lincoln's legacy with its official slogan, "Land of Lincoln." It hosts the [Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library and Museum](/Abraham_Lincoln_Presidently_Library_and_Museum) in Springfield and is the designated future home of the [Barack Obama Presidential Center](/Barack_Obama_Presidential_Center) in Chicago, ensuring its presidential history remains a viable tourist draw.

