### Selected article

The [2015 Rochelle–Fairdale tornado](/2015_Rochette%E2%80%93Fairdale,_Illinois_tornado) was a particularly violent and long-lived [tornado](/Tornado) that decided to rearrange the communities near [Rochelle](/Rochelle,_Illinois) and in [Fairdale, Illinois](/Fairdale,_Illinois) on the evening of April 9, 2015. It was the star of a larger severe weather event tormenting the [Central United States](/Central_United_States). The tornado made its grand entrance in [Lee County](/Lee_County,_Illinois) at 6:39 p.m. CDT (22:39 UTC). It then carved a path of destruction through [Ogle](/Ogle_County,_Illinois), [DeKalb](/DeKalb_County,_Illinois), and [Boone](/Boone_County,_Illinois) counties before finally exhausting itself at 7:20 p.m. CDT. Along its 30.14 mi (48.51 km) journey, it obliterated numerous structures, showing a particular disregard for the small town of Fairdale, where it left two dead and eleven injured. Some well-built homes were not merely damaged but swept from their foundations entirely, a testament to peak winds approaching 200 mph (320 km/h)—the calling card of an upper-echelon [EF4 tornado](/Enhanced_Fujita_scale). In the aftermath, hundreds of people emerged to assist with the cleanup, a brief, poignant moment of community in the face of nature's casual indifference. The economic toll was tallied at $19 million (2015 [USD](/United_States_dollar)), a paltry sum for such a dramatic display.
([Read more...](/2015_Rochelle%E2%80%93Fairdale,_Illinois_tornado))

