Image 39: The dome of the [Illinois State Capitol](/Illinois_State_Capitol). The interior features a plaster frieze painted to look like bronze, depicting scenes from state history, and a stained glass replica of the [State Seal](/Seal_of_Illinois) in the oculus. Construction began in 1869 and dragged on for twenty years.
Photo credit: Daniel Schwen (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 40: The [Willis Tower](/Willis_Tower) (once the Sears Tower), which held the title of world's tallest building from 1973 to 2004. Its innovative [bundled tube structure](/Tube_(structure)) was the brainchild of [Bruce Graham](/Bruce_Graham) and [Fazlur Khan](/Fazlur_Rahman_Khan).
Photo credit: [Soakologist](/User:Soakologist) (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 41: A 1926 [Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad](/Chicago,_Burlington_and_Quincy_Railroad) [Railway Post Office](/Railway_Post_Office) car, now preserved at the [Illinois Railway Museum](/Illinois_Railway_Museum) in [Union](/Union,_Illinois).
Photo credit: Sean Lamb (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 42: The Twenty Acre Dairy Barn, the first of the experimental [University of Illinois round barns](/University_of_Illinois_round_barns). Designed in 1908 for the [University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign](/University_of_Illinois_at_Urbana%E2%80%93Champaign).
Photo credit: Daniel Schwen (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 43: A [Canada goose](/Canada_goose) (Branta canadensis) enjoying a swim in [Palatine](/Palatine,_Illinois). They are everywhere.
Photo credit: Joe Ravi (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 44: The shore of [Lake Michigan](/Lake_Michigan) at [Illinois Beach State Park](/Illinois_Beach_State_Park) in [Lake County](/Lake_County,_Illinois).
Image credit: Yinan Chen (photographer), Slick (upload) (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 45: The [Lincoln Tomb](/Lincoln_Tomb) in [Oak Ridge Cemetery](/Oak_Ridge_Cemetery), [Springfield](/Springfield,_Illinois). [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln) is interred here with [Mary Todd Lincoln](/Mary_Todd_Lincoln) and three of their sons. The tomb, designed by [Larkin Goldsmith Mead](/Larkin_Goldsmith_Mead), was completed in 1874.
Photo credit: David Jones (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 46: An artist's rendering of [Kincaid Mounds](/Kincaid_Mounds_State_Historic_Site), a city of the [Mississippian culture](/Mississippian_culture) at its peak, located near the Ohio River on the border of modern-day [Massac](/Massac_County,_Illinois) and [Pope](/Pope_County,_Illinois) counties.
Image credit: [H. Rowe](/User:Heironymous_Rowe) (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 47: [Magnolia Manor](/Magnolia_Manor_(Cairo,_Illinois)) in [Cairo](/Cairo,_Illinois), built in 1869 by businessman Charles A. Galigher.
Photo credit: MuZemike (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 48: The [Cairo Mississippi River Bridge](/Cairo_Mississippi_River_Bridge) near the meeting point of the [Mississippi](/Mississippi_River) and [Ohio](/Ohio_River) Rivers at [Cairo](/Cairo,_Illinois), the state's lowest point. The bridge was built in 1929.
Image credit: Nick Jordan (photographer), Fredddie (upload) (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 49: The water tower and barracks at [Fort Sheridan](/Sheridan_Reserve_Center) in 1898. The main buildings were constructed between 1889 and 1910 by the firm [Holabird & Roche](/Holabird_%26_Root).
Image credit: [Detroit Photographic Co.](/Detroit_Photographic_Co.); [Bathgems](/User:Bathgems) (upload) (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 50: "Let Go–But Stand By": A photo of [Frances Willard](/Frances_Willard) from her 1895 book on learning to ride the new [safety bicycle](/Safety_bicycle), which became improbably [linked with women's emancipation](/Bicycling_and_feminism).
Image credit: [Frances E. Willard](/Frances_E._Willard) (book author), [Woman's Temperance Publishing Association](/Woman%27s_Temperance_Publishing_Association) and [Fleming H. Revell Co.](/Baker_Publishing_Group) (publishers), [HathiTrust](/HathiTrust) (digitization), [Dennis Bratland](/User:Dennis_Bratland) (upload) (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 51: A [great blue heron](/Great_blue_heron) (Ardea herodias) flying with nesting material. There's a colony of about twenty nests nearby, forming a noisy, avian suburb.
Image credit: PhotoBobil (photographer), Snowmanradio (upload), PetarM (digital retouching) (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 52: The [Purple Heart](/Purple_Heart) memorial at [Oak Ridge Cemetery](/Oak_Ridge_Cemetery) in [Springfield, Illinois](/Springfield,_Illinois).
Image credit: [PhilDaBirdMan](/User:PhilDaBirdMan) (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 53: [Chris Young](/Chris_Young_(baseball_pitcher)) [winding up](/Pitching_position) for a [four-seam fastball](/Four-seam_fastball) in the [bullpen](/Bullpen) before a 2007 game. The iconic [Wrigley Field](/Wrigley_Field) scoreboard looms in the background.
Image credit: [TonyTheTiger](/User:TonyTheTiger) (photographer) and [Jjron](/User:Jjron) (editing) (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 54: "The Great Presidential Puzzle": A [chromolithograph](/Chromolithograph) cartoon about the chaotic [1880 Republican National Convention](/1880_Republican_National_Convention) in Chicago. It depicts [Roscoe Conkling](/Roscoe_Conkling), leader of the party's [Stalwarts](/Stalwarts) faction, playing a puzzle game with the heads of presidential hopefuls, a parody of the [15 puzzle](/15_puzzle).
Image credit: Mayer, Merkel, & Ottmann (lithographers); James Albert Wales (artist); Jujutacular (digital retouching) (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 55: Photograph of [Rockford](/Rockford,_Illinois) pilot [Elizabeth L. Gardner](/Elizabeth_L._Gardner) of the [WASPs](/Women_Airforce_Service_Pilots) at [Harlingen Army Air Field](/Harlingen_Air_Force_Base), Texas.
Image credit: [U.S. Dept. of the Air Force](/United_States_Department_of_the_Air_Force) (photograph); [National Archives Catalog](/National_Archives_and_Records_Administration) (digital file); Junkyardsparkle, Hohum, Bammesk (digital retouching) (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

•

Image 56: The [Vandalia State House](/Vandalia_State_House_State_Historic_Site), the former state capitol from 1836, now maintained by the [Illinois Historic Preservation Agency](/Illinois_Historic_Preservation_Agency).
Photo credit: Art davis (from [Portal:Illinois/Selected picture](/Portal:Illinois/Selected_picture))

